## Glossary

### Search engine

A website that can be used to find and explore internet content. The most popular search engines are Google, Bing and Yahoo.

### SEO

Search engine optimization (SEO) is a methodology of strategies, techniques and tactics used to increase the amount of visitors to a website by obtaining a high-ranking placement in the search results page of a search engine (SERP) like Google or Bing. 

### On-page optimizations

The strategic incorporation of keyword-optimized content into important areas of a web page so that search engines can easily crawl and determine the subject of that page. This includes both unseen content (such as metadata) and relevant text that’s actually visible on the page.

### Off-page optimizations

SEO practices other than what’s performed on your website itself. Ensuring that your site is recognized and favorably referenced across the web results in good off-page SEO and will cause the search engines to treat your site better. Important off-page tactics include link building and a solid social media strategy.

### Pay-Per Click (PPC)

Also known as cost per click (CPC), is an internet advertising model used to direct traffic to websites, in which an advertiser pays a publisher when the ad is clicked.

### Metadata

Data that tells search engines what your website is about.

###  Meta Description

A ~160 character snippet that summarizes a page's content. Search engines show the Meta description in search results, so optimizing the Meta description is a very important aspect of on-page SEO.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

### Page Title

Title tags define the title of a document or webpage. It is meant to give an accurate description of page’s content and should be between 50-60 characters. 

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

### H1 Tag

Used to mark the importance of a heading text on a webpage.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

### Image Alt Text

A short but descriptive phrase used to tell web site viewers the nature or contents of an image.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

### Hreflang Tag

An attribute that tells Google which language you are using on a specific page, so the search engine can serve results to users searching in the appropriate language. This is utilized for all the Sub-Zero &amp; Wolf international sites.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

### Sitemap

A special document that provides a map of all the pages on a website, making it easier for a search engine to index a website. The main site&#39;s sitemap can be found here: [http://www.subzero-wolf.com/sitemap](http://www.subzero-wolf.com/sitemap)

### Page Speed

A measurement of how fast the content on your page loads.

### Bounce rate

The percentage of users who enter a site and then leave it within a short amount of time and without viewing any other pages.

## SEO Best Practices

1. Complete **keyword research** so you have an understanding of search trends. Start with branded terms, how are you ranking in your country? Then shift to non-branded terms (such as product types, recipes, videos, etc.). Which keywords rank high and where are these opportunities for improvement? Utilize search volume insights in your content, Meta data and paid media strategies. 

2. Familiarize yourself with your **competitor&#39;s website**. What language are they using to talk about themselves and their products? What keywords are they ranking on organically and do they have paid search campaigns running? This can be helpful in developing your own descriptors and a paid search plan.

3. Spend time developing **strong Meta data**** in your site&#39;s native language**. You can review/translate the Meta data on the primary US site, although we recommend modifying based on cultural references and keyword research completed in your own country. To find current meta data:
  1. Navigate to a page on the site
  2. Right click and select &quot;View page source&quot; or hit CLT+U
  3. Hit CLT+F to open the &quot;find feature&quot; and search for &quot;meta&quot; (usually at the top of the page in the first ~20 lines)
  4. Review the title, description and name.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

4. Keep a pulse on your **overall traffic, conversion metrics and user engagement** (time on site, pages/session, bounce rate, etc.). Knowing which sections of your site drive the most engagement can help with developing campaigns and new ideas. This information can be found in your monthly site performance report.

5. Pay close attention to landing page engagement metrics by channel. It&#39;s important that your organic and paid search landing pages have **low bounce rates** , low exit rates and a substantial portion of new sessions. This information can also be found in your monthly site performance report.
